President Obama will be awarding the Medal of Valor to thirteen public safety officers on May 16. The Medal of Valor is given to officers who have shown exceptional courage in trying to save or protect others. The event will be open to the press, but space is limited. Media members must RSVP to attend. The Medal of Valor is the highest national award for valor given to a public safety officer and is awarded by the President or his designee. The recipients of the medal have been nominated by their employing agencies and recommended by the Medal of Valor Review Board. The recipients have exhibited bravery and composure in various situations, such as subduing a knife-wielding assailant, apprehending a gunman, and saving the lives of students during a school shooting.